  footnotes: []
english:
  title: At Cloud Peak Temple
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Grasping vines, I climb to the clouded peak,
    Looking down, the world spreads empty before me.
    Thousand mountains rest like lines on my palm,
    Ten thousand matters dissolve within my heart.
    The pagoda's shadow merges with snow at the sun's edge,
    Pine songs drift on winds that split the sky.
    Clouds and rosy mists must laugh at me—
    I turn my steps back down into the dusty world.
  footnotes:
    - Cloud Peak Temple (雲峯寺) is a Buddhist monastery in Korea, likely visited by the poet during his travels.
    - The classical allusion in the poem reflects the Buddhist and Daoist themes common in Tang-period Korean poetry, particularly the tension between enlightenment and worldly return.
    - The palm metaphor draws on both Buddhist meditation imagery and classical Chinese poetic convention, suggesting both detachment and contained wisdom.
